00:18.785 --> 00:19.318
ADMISSION

00:19.319 --> 00:22.287
<i>An admissions officer
must have a strong constitution...</i>

00:22.288 --> 00:23.956
<i>to be on the receiving end of...</i>

00:23.957 --> 00:26.725
<i>..-an entire nation's application panic.</i>

00:26.726 --> 00:31.726
<i>To endure the frustration and anger
of all the so-called millennial parents,</i>

00:31.765 --> 00:32.798
<i>who just realized...</i>

00:32.799 --> 00:35.200
- Come on, hurry up!
- God, mom, relax.

00:35.201 --> 00:37.836
<i>There isn't room
for every perfectly nurtured,</i>

00:37.837 --> 00:39.874
<i>organically fed,
well-tutored offspring.</i>

00:39.973 --> 00:41.673
OK, I'm your tour guide.

00:41.674 --> 00:43.375
There's no point
in trying to impress me.

00:43.376 --> 00:46.912
I have absolutely no power
over your fate here.

00:46.913 --> 00:48.914
The people with the power
are right in there.

00:48.915 --> 00:51.122
The Admissions officers.

00:51.317 --> 00:54.520
And no,
that sign is not an omen.

00:54.521 --> 00:56.288
Except for some of you.

00:56.289 --> 00:57.956
Almost all of you, actually.

00:57.957 --> 00:59.425
We had twenty six thousand,

00:59.426 --> 01:02.895
two hundred and forty one
applications last year.

01:02.896 --> 01:05.397
One thousand, three hundred
and eight of those applicants...

01:05.397 --> 01:07.469
are attending school here.

01:14.507 --> 01:17.709
James, tours leave at 9:15.
It is 9:25.

01:17.710 --> 01:21.346
Sorry, I thought I'd wait.
We had a late arrival.

01:21.347 --> 01:24.453
I'm sorry, our GPS lied.

01:25.452 --> 01:28.120
No worries, Mrs...

01:28.121 --> 01:29.464
...Lafont.

01:30.023 --> 01:31.832
Welcome to Princeton.

01:33.827 --> 01:35.961
So what's the secret
to getting in?

01:35.962 --> 01:37.498
The secret.

01:41.401 --> 01:42.868
Just be yourself.

01:42.869 --> 01:47.409
If this is the right place for you,
then this is where you'll end up.

01:48.641 --> 01:50.742
- James?
- Ok, let's go see Princeton.

01:50.743 --> 01:51.944
We're going to play
a fun game.

01:51.945 --> 01:54.246
It's called spot
the Nobel Prize winner.

01:54.247 --> 01:55.647
<i>What's the secret
to getting in?</i>

01:55.648 --> 01:57.249
<i>There has to be one, right?</i>

01:57.250 --> 01:58.317
<i>Well, there is.</i>

01:58.318 --> 02:00.719
<i>But I can't tell you.
Not yet.</i>

02:00.720 --> 02:03.322
<i>What I can tell you
is everyone thinks we're sadists.</i>

02:03.323 --> 02:06.191
<i>That we like saying no.
This is not true.</i>

02:06.192 --> 02:08.293
- No.
- Portia.

02:08.294 --> 02:08.926
<i>No no no.</i>

02:08.928 --> 02:11.530
You're second reader
on my territory this season.

02:11.531 --> 02:13.799
Yes, I know.
As are you on mine.

02:13.800 --> 02:16.246
That's the way it works.

02:18.271 --> 02:21.980
I'll just wail
until you catch up with me.

02:24.144 --> 02:26.678
<i>We are in this job
for one reason.</i>

02:26.679 --> 02:28.113
- <i>Hello?</i>
- <i>Is this Portia Nathan?</i>

02:28.114 --> 02:28.580
<i>To say.</i>

02:28.581 --> 02:29.214
Yes.

02:29.215 --> 02:31.583
Wow, I didn't think I'd gel you.
It's John Pressman...

02:31.584 --> 02:34.386
...from the New Quest School
in Keene, New Hampshire.

02:34.387 --> 02:34.987
OK.

02:34.988 --> 02:38.023
Yeah, I sent you a few e-mails
and left a couple messages.

02:38.024 --> 02:39.091
Listen, thank you for calling.

02:39.092 --> 02:41.326
Can you please e-mail me your information
and I will call you back?

02:41.327 --> 02:42.327
<i>Hey, not so rough.</i>

02:42.328 --> 02:44.096
How'd you like
to have your udder yanked like that?

02:44.097 --> 02:46.465
- Excuse me?
- Sorry, I was just talking to a student.

02:46.466 --> 02:49.601
People, everyone, please.

02:49.602 --> 02:51.904
I have a couple
of announcements.

02:51.905 --> 02:53.572
There is an announcement.

02:53.573 --> 02:55.207
Portia,
we're a new developmental school...

02:55.208 --> 02:57.743
and we have our first
graduating class this year.

02:57.744 --> 03:00.312
I know you're going to be making
your school visits in the next few weeks.

03:00.313 --> 03:02.014
<i>I'd like for you
to visit our campus.</i>

03:02.015 --> 03:04.816
<i>Our kids would gain a lot from it
and I think you would too.</i>

03:04.817 --> 03:06.818
Right, I will look into it.
Gotta go.

03:06.819 --> 03:08.887
You know,
I went to Dartmouth, same time as you.

03:08.888 --> 03:11.156
Bye.
Thank you for calling.

03:11.157 --> 03:15.127
So we're breaking records
in application numbers, naturally...

03:15.128 --> 03:18.931
...because we've been
number one for so long.

03:18.932 --> 03:21.776
Number one until today.

03:22.202 --> 03:25.775
Princeton has just fallen
to number two.

03:27.307 --> 03:31.577
What this means
is that we all have to work harder than ever...

03:31.578 --> 03:33.845
...because I want to go out on top.

03:33.846 --> 03:36.815
Yes,
you see the rumors are true.

03:36.816 --> 03:38.817
I've decided to retire.

03:38.818 --> 03:43.021
And pass the baton
to a worthy successor.

03:43.022 --> 03:45.724
I'm spending an extra four days
in the Andover-Hotchkiss triangle.

03:45.725 --> 03:49.494
And I've added five full days to the San Francisco
Bay Area and Northern California.

03:49.495 --> 03:51.763
And I've added a number
of new schools.

03:51.764 --> 03:55.100
In fact, I was just talking
to the co-founder of Quest.-.

03:55.101 --> 03:58.303
...a developmental high school
with their first year of college applicants.

03:58.304 --> 04:00.105
Clarence,
we're going to be back on lop.

04:00.106 --> 04:01.540
We're going to make that happen.

04:01.541 --> 04:03.953
By working together.
Right, Portia?

04:04.777 --> 04:06.188
Absolutely.

04:06.613 --> 04:09.348
As a mother myself,
I know the importance of teamwork.

04:09.349 --> 04:13.118
And I am not a mother,
but I know the importance of it loo.

04:13.119 --> 04:14.792
Can't go it alone.

04:16.589 --> 04:18.190
Good.

04:18.190 --> 04:21.392
Because you two
are my superstars...

04:21.394 --> 04:24.997
...and nothing would make me happier
than if one of you...

04:24.998 --> 04:29.003
.-.were to have this office next year-.

04:39.012 --> 04:40.184
OK.

04:40.813 --> 04:43.726
Class of 2016.

04:46.185 --> 04:49.454
Pediatric surgery best combines
my love of children...

04:49.455 --> 04:53.492
...of science, and my desire
to give back to my community.

04:53.493 --> 04:55.927
Yes, but you didn't challenge
yourself academically.

04:55.928 --> 04:59.671
B's in Physics
and you didn't take AP Chem.

05:02.368 --> 05:03.235
UNLIKELY

05:03.236 --> 05:04.403
<i>Princeton's awesome.</i>

05:04.404 --> 05:09.478
Since 1841, every male in my family
has attended the place.

05:10.643 --> 05:12.244
Student Body President.

05:12.245 --> 05:14.112
And gymnastics
national champion.

05:14.113 --> 05:16.848
Educated family.
Privileged upbringing.

05:16.849 --> 05:18.350
Unfair advantage?

05:18.351 --> 05:21.520
2400 on the SAT. 4.5 GPA.

05:21.521 --> 05:24.189
And my poetry,
written in my mother's psych ward...

05:24.190 --> 05:27.492
...will be published by Knopf.
And my father is Cuban.

05:27.493 --> 05:29.200
And in a wheelchair.

05:32.865 --> 05:34.666
- Can I gel some advice?
- No.

05:34.667 --> 05:36.868
Applicalus interruptus.
You know the rule.

05:36.869 --> 05:39.509
Never start a folder
if you can't finish it.

05:41.040 --> 05:43.041
I have to start over anyway.
OK.

05:43.042 --> 05:46.244
This kid from Alaska,
Aput Kunayak.

05:46.245 --> 05:49.214
High grades,
but low scores.

05:49.215 --> 05:52.451
President of ten clubs,
but that might be because of his ADD.

05:52.452 --> 05:54.953
We want to accept people
who will succeed here.

05:54.954 --> 05:59.524
You know, I once fought for a bipolar Inuit girl
and she lasted nineteen days.

05:59.525 --> 06:01.793
- Do you think he might fail?
- Maybe.

06:01.794 --> 06:03.535
I like him.

06:05.732 --> 06:07.040
It's so hard.

06:07.333 --> 06:09.468
You can't take it
so personally.

06:09.469 --> 06:12.416
You have to toughen up
or you won't last here either.

06:12.572 --> 06:14.552
Now outsies.
I'm swamped.

06:15.475 --> 06:16.920
<i>Portia?</i>

06:17.410 --> 06:19.185
I hope it's you.

06:19.445 --> 06:20.753
Thank you.

06:21.381 --> 06:22.883
Back to work.

06:35.194 --> 06:36.172
<i>Portia!</i>

06:36.729 --> 06:37.329
Hello?

06:37.330 --> 06:39.831
Portia?
Portia? Portia...

06:39.832 --> 06:42.033
I'm so sorry,
I've got an emergency.

06:42.034 --> 06:44.469
Can you just watch the kids
while I run to the vet?

06:44.470 --> 06:46.438
Because Richard's
at his Faulkner seminar.

06:46.439 --> 06:47.439
Me?

06:47.440 --> 06:49.107
Well, Mark should have been home
twenty minutes ago,

06:49.108 --> 06:51.343
and it's our poetry night, and...

06:51.344 --> 06:54.848
...really, I'm the last person
you want watching your kids.

07:00.720 --> 07:01.824
Quiet!

07:02.522 --> 07:05.257
- Did someone die?
- Rachael's dog is sick.

07:05.258 --> 07:06.601
She begged me.

07:07.026 --> 07:08.801
Good times.

07:11.030 --> 07:13.874
- I've got essays to grade.
- No.

07:19.472 --> 07:22.174
It's OK.
Mommy's here.

07:22.175 --> 07:23.241
What did you do to them?

07:23.242 --> 07:25.744
Rachael,
you know Portia's not good with kids.

07:25.745 --> 07:27.245
It's not her fault.

07:27.246 --> 07:30.615
Kids just don't take
to some people.

07:30.616 --> 07:32.823
I don't know
what you were thinking.

07:33.286 --> 07:34.953
Sorry, he's right.

07:34.954 --> 07:37.856
They're like pit bulls.
They can smell fear.

07:37.857 --> 07:39.324
Good night.

07:39.325 --> 07:40.633
Take them all.

07:49.035 --> 07:52.170
You know, if I gel Clarence's job,
this will be my last travel season.

07:52.171 --> 07:53.371
Lovely and wonderful.

07:53.372 --> 07:56.408
I've got everything planned out.
I'll be back in time for the department lunch.

07:56.409 --> 07:57.943
And I've ordered everything,
you just need to pick up the...

07:57.944 --> 08:02.581
...chicken and I will stop and get
the famous bean salad on my way home.

08:02.582 --> 08:05.250
The famous bean salad.

08:05.251 --> 08:08.153
Is that horrible Woolf woman
going to be there?

08:08.154 --> 08:12.257
Helen is the preeminent
Virginia Woolf scholar.

08:12.258 --> 08:13.792
It was quite a coup
to get her from Cambridge.

08:13.793 --> 08:16.895
But I think
she has other plans.

08:16.896 --> 08:18.705
Lovely and wonderful.

08:24.270 --> 08:25.977
I like this life.

08:26.372 --> 08:29.819
- I do, I do.
- Good. So do I.

08:31.611 --> 08:34.922
It's so wonderfully...

08:35.081 --> 08:36.081
...simple.

08:36.082 --> 08:39.495
Well, we're simple folk.

08:43.722 --> 08:44.723
Woof!

08:44.724 --> 08:45.724
Excuse me?

08:45.725 --> 08:48.827
You just patted me
on the head like a dog.

08:48.828 --> 08:50.273
Did I?

08:50.963 --> 08:52.738
Good doggie.

09:12.251 --> 09:13.852
Hi.

09:13.853 --> 09:15.520
Thank you so much for coming.

09:15.521 --> 09:17.422
My pleasure.
We love Deerfield students.

09:17.423 --> 09:19.190
I'm so pleased.
Good.

09:19.191 --> 09:21.831
- Can I help you bring in your things?
- Yes, please.

09:29.602 --> 09:31.002
<i>Princeton.</i>

09:31.003 --> 09:35.281
<i>In the nation's service
and in the service of all nations.</i>

09:37.009 --> 09:42.584
So, you all want to know
the secret formula for getting in, right?

09:42.915 --> 09:45.984
Take out your pens.
Write this down.

09:45.985 --> 09:48.363
There is no secret formula.

09:49.722 --> 09:51.656
<i>Left on Pony Run Drive.</i>

09:51.657 --> 09:53.959
But I will tell you
what not to do.

09:53.960 --> 09:56.127
No champagne,
no baked goods,

09:56.128 --> 09:59.064
and when you phone,
it is noted in your file.

09:59.065 --> 10:02.634
So put the reins
on those eager parents of yours.

10:02.635 --> 10:04.035
We're looking for passion.

10:04.036 --> 10:06.304
Whatever it's for,
doesn't matter.

10:06.305 --> 10:07.138
Passion.

10:07.139 --> 10:09.074
<i>Right on Shady Lane.</i>

10:09.075 --> 10:13.678
Does that mean every Princeton
undergraduate is a genius or a prodigy?

10:13.679 --> 10:14.980
Absolutely not.

10:14.981 --> 10:17.816
Although we certainly
wouldn't hold it against you.

10:17.817 --> 10:19.592
Almost enough for everybody.

10:24.957 --> 10:29.463
Recalcu Eating.
Recalculating. Recalculating-.

10:33.799 --> 10:36.801
Make a U turn
as soon as possible.

10:36.802 --> 10:38.008
The New Quest School

10:39.171 --> 10:40.013
No Service

10:56.088 --> 10:57.355
<i>HEY-</i>

10:57.356 --> 10:58.630
Hi.

10:59.025 --> 11:01.559
Portia Nathan,
Princeton Admissions office.

11:01.560 --> 11:03.194
I know. I'm John.

11:03.195 --> 11:05.664
Yes, and you said
you went to Dartmouth?

11:05.665 --> 11:09.100
Yeah, and my dad,
and his dad, and his dad.

11:09.101 --> 11:10.201
A legacy-

11:10.202 --> 11:12.773
A legacy of what,
I'm not really sure.

11:13.272 --> 11:15.874
So you're chopping
some wood here?

11:15.875 --> 11:19.277
I'm showing them how to build
a sustainable irrigation system.

11:19.278 --> 11:20.945
This is my third world
development class.

11:20.946 --> 11:22.881
Well, nice axe.

11:22.882 --> 11:24.520
Great axe.

11:25.718 --> 11:28.164
- So let's gel to it.
- Yeah.

11:44.870 --> 11:46.071
Hi there.

11:46.072 --> 11:50.680
You all want to know the secret formula
for getting in, right?

11:53.145 --> 11:55.648
Well, take out your pens.

11:59.719 --> 12:01.426
Take them out.

12:04.156 --> 12:05.464
Yes?

12:06.025 --> 12:08.359
I'll tell you what I'd like to know.

12:08.360 --> 12:10.929
Why should I apply
to an elitist institution...

12:10.930 --> 12:14.666
.-.with a history of anti-black, anti-gay,
and anti-female oppression?

12:14.667 --> 12:16.768
Well, actually,
I reject that stereotype-

12:16.769 --> 12:17.902
Speaking of rejection,

12:17.903 --> 12:20.939
don't you reject 99.9 percent
of your applicants?

12:20.940 --> 12:23.808
And don't you just want to drum up applications
to keep your number one position...

12:23.809 --> 12:25.076
on U.S. News
and World Report?

12:25.077 --> 12:27.645
Well actually,
I think it's number two this year, right?

12:27.646 --> 12:30.648
- Yes, but-
- No, I'm sure it's an aberration.

12:30.649 --> 12:33.017
Don't people just need
a college degree if you want lo pursue...

12:33.018 --> 12:35.787
the societally
approved definition of success?

12:35.788 --> 12:38.623
Yeah, wouldn't you be better
off sitting in your room reading books...

12:38.624 --> 12:40.158
instead of spending all that money?

12:40.159 --> 12:41.793
I'm sorry, _
are you a senior?

12:41.794 --> 12:43.261
No, I'm in sixth grade.

12:43.262 --> 12:45.997
Yeah, Portia,
this is my son, Nelson.

12:45.998 --> 12:48.032
I'm adopted.
I was born in Uganda.

12:48.033 --> 12:50.809
- Love you, buddy.
- OK, dad.

12:51.504 --> 12:54.939
I thought it would be educational
for him to sit in on this.

12:54.940 --> 12:56.975
How's it going so far?
Are you learning a lot?

12:56.976 --> 12:59.244
Kind of.
Half and half.

12:59.245 --> 13:01.913
- Well there you go.
- OK. Right.

13:01.914 --> 13:05.016
Well, Nelson, sure...

13:05.017 --> 13:08.486
sitting in a room and reading books
would be very cost effective, but-

13:08.487 --> 13:10.388
Princeton is a corporation.

13:10.389 --> 13:12.624
No different
than an oil company.

13:12.625 --> 13:15.260
We should be educating ourselves
to be citizens of the world...

13:15.261 --> 13:17.362
and not of some guarded
suburban enclave.

13:17.363 --> 13:21.869
What we want is to leave the planet
better than we found it.

13:25.805 --> 13:28.445
OK. Well.
Good luck with that.

13:29.141 --> 13:30.017
Wail, wait.

13:30.309 --> 13:33.778
I want to hear about Princeton, please.

13:33.779 --> 13:37.048
OK, fine.
But first, I have a question for all of you.

13:37.049 --> 13:40.251
Just how will you leave
the planet better?

13:40.252 --> 13:43.254
Will you eradicate disease?
You're going to need a medical degree.

13:43.255 --> 13:45.990
If you want to create new drug therapies,
that's a PhD.

13:45.991 --> 13:50.128
Do you want to defend the innocent
and secure justice for all?

13:50.129 --> 13:53.731
I regret to inform you
that you will have to go to law school.

13:53.732 --> 13:56.501
There are plenty
of college graduates out there...

13:56.502 --> 13:59.671
...ardently hoping to leave the world
better than they found it.

13:59.672 --> 14:01.940
We are looking
for those people!

14:01.941 --> 14:07.323
Students with blazing minds
and hearts who will change the goddamn world!

14:11.217 --> 14:13.885
All right, Portia.
Well done!

14:13.886 --> 14:17.026
I bet you guys
feel like bunch of assholes.

14:21.894 --> 14:22.660
Sorry,
I probably should have warned you.

14:22.661 --> 14:24.429
Sorry,
I probably should have warned you.

14:24.430 --> 14:27.131
We tend to encourage
that sort of spirited debate here.

14:27.132 --> 14:28.600
But you did well.

14:28.601 --> 14:30.945
You can hit a curveball.

14:32.037 --> 14:35.506
You know, I'd really like
to introduce you to somebody.

14:35.507 --> 14:37.342
This is Jeremiah Balakian.

14:37.343 --> 14:39.010
He's a very special student.

14:39.011 --> 14:41.079
My parents work in a mini-mart.

14:41.080 --> 14:42.480
They're not very educated.

14:42.481 --> 14:44.883
Do you think that matters?

14:44.884 --> 14:47.218
Of course not.
It's your application.

14:47.219 --> 14:49.654
Maybe I should apply then.
Princeton seems like a cool place.

14:49.655 --> 14:51.389
It's very cool.

14:51.390 --> 14:53.391
So you're saying
I should apply?

14:53.392 --> 14:55.126
You know,
I'm not really your typical student.

14:55.127 --> 14:59.473
My brain sort of goes
on a little Walkabout, you know?

14:59.765 --> 15:02.100
Yes, you should apply.

15:02.101 --> 15:04.903
And if you would like
to visit the campus...

15:04.904 --> 15:07.906
...we can match you up with an undergrad
and you can spend the night in his room.

15:07.907 --> 15:08.973
That sounds great.

15:08.974 --> 15:12.210
Then you could hang out
and gel to know each other.

15:12.211 --> 15:14.612
Well, I don't really hang out
with the applicants.

15:14.613 --> 15:16.247
- That's not how it works.
- Right.

15:16.248 --> 15:17.515
Because
there's over twenty thousand of them.

15:17.516 --> 15:18.650
Exactly.

15:18.651 --> 15:21.632
Still,
I think you should gel to know this one.

15:23.188 --> 15:24.923
So, Portia,
like the Merchant of Venice?

15:24.924 --> 15:25.490
Yes.

15:25.491 --> 15:27.926
My mother thought if she named me
that I would grow up to be wise.

15:27.927 --> 15:29.193
I'm lucky
she didn't name me Athena.

15:29.194 --> 15:30.962
Or Minerva.
Or Sophie.

15:30.963 --> 15:32.196
Except a lot of people
are named Sophie.

15:32.197 --> 15:33.498
They probably don't even know
what their name means.

15:33.499 --> 15:35.266
Or Metis.
That would be really strange.

15:35.267 --> 15:39.871
Or if your name was Aushenaya
or lﬂok or Saraswati.

15:39.872 --> 15:41.572
I think you got lucky.

15:41.573 --> 15:44.417
If you had to be called something
that stands for wisdom.

15:47.980 --> 15:50.381
Well, thanks for this.

15:50.382 --> 15:53.556
I have to go.
I have robotics class.

15:57.122 --> 15:59.390
